First, let's find A × B, which is the Cartesian product of A and B. This is the set of all ordered pairs (a, b) where a is in A and b is in B.

A × B = {(1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4)}

Now, let's find the symmetric difference (△) of (A × B) and B. The symmetric difference of two sets is the set of elements which are in either of the sets, but not in their intersection.

(A × B) △ B = {(1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4)}

Note that the symmetric difference of B and B is the empty set, since all elements in B are also in B.

B △ B = {}

Now let's find A × (B △ B). Since B △ B is an empty set, the Cartesian product of A and the empty set will also be an empty set.

A × (B △ B) = {}

Now, let's compare (A × B) △ B and A × (B △ B):

(A × B) △ B = {(1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4)}
A × (B △ B) = {}

Since (A × B) △ B is not equal to A × (B △ B), we have shown that (A × B) △ B is not equal to A × (B △ B).
